author: @VigilanteVegan
comment:
Maybe I’m in the minority here, but I’ll say it. Just because Sony, Fox, and Disney are three separate movie studios, does NOT mean the in-story explanation has to be that the characters in the respective three are in their own distinct universe.

Case in point, I thought the post-credit Venom scene in No Way Home was unnecessary, as there’s no reason for Sony to put themselves in that hole rather than have the implication that Tom Holland’s Spider-man is somewhere out there in that world, just offscreen & not referenced.

That being said, just because MCU acquired the rights to Deadpool, does NOT mean there needs to be in-story explanation of him traveling from Fox-verse to Marvel-verse and bringing Wolverine with him through a portal. I’m all for him referencing it breaking the fourth wall, but actually doing it as a major part of the plot is another story.

The most grounded way of doing it is to imply the X-men, Deadpool, and Wolverine have been in the same world alongside other Marvel characters all along. Just because past X-men instalments didn’t reference them before, that’s perfectly fine.

The idea of characters switching universes because they change movie studios is absurd and unnecessary. The early Jason movies were distributed by Paramount. Then it switched to New Line Cinema. They never showed Jason hopping into a New Line portal so he could fight Freddy Krueger. 😂

I’m tired of multiverse stories. They’re great every vicennium as a nostalgic treat, but as a plot device for every other movie, they must go. They make the writer’s job very easy because they’re are infinite possibilities. There are no real threats and stake because a character can hop on over to Fox-verse and nab an alternate version of someone who just died. Iron Man’s death has no meaning really since they can nab a new one over in Sony-verse who happens to look like Tom Cruise. Nothing matters.

Now, compare to a story like in “The Batman” which has a grounded story without portals and potions to fill a 3-hour runtime where real things are at stake. When people die they die. These stories are harder to write. As I said, the multiverse can be fun, but it needs to go as a plot device. Ever since No Way Home, it’s being used too much.

author: @hezsoca
comment:
Kedves Szinkronrajongók és Barátok!
Az elmúlt hetekben rengetegen kerestetek azzal kapcsolatban, hogy felveszem-e még a "szinkronkarmokat".
Akkor türelmet kértem.
Az elmúlt 24 évben összesen 8 alkalommal szinkronizáltam Hugh Jackmant különböző képregényfilmekben, valamint egyszer a "közös karakterünket" rajzfilmes formában is.
Az új film előzetesét szervezési okokból nem tudtam elvállalni, aznap a 21. Klasszikus Erdélyi Magyar Irodalom Kárpát-medencei Prózafelolvasó Versenyre hívtak meg díszvendégként, amit már korábban nagy örömmel fogadtam el.
Az előzetes felvételével azonban nem lehetett várni, így végül azt nem én szinkronizáltam.
Ezt követően - legnagyobb meglepetésemre - castingot kért a megrendelő.
Bár nem tudom, hogy 8 film után milyen új információt nyújthat egy ilyen felvétel a megrendelő számára, de részt vettem rajta.
Közel 3 hét után ma azt az információt kaptuk,
hogy a Disney (?) úgy döntött, hogy nem tart igényt a hangomra.
A fentieket azért tartottam fontosnak leírni, hogy a hírt tőlem tudjátok meg, illetve hogy ne merülhessenek fel olyan esetleges félreértések, mint hogy az anyagiakon múlt.
Nagyon megható volt olvasni az előzetes magyar változatára érkező kommenteket, az időközben kapott számtalan kedves levelet.
Valódi elismerèst csak ès kizárólag
a közönség adhat!
Nagyon köszönöm mindenkinek!
A Disney döntésètől függetlenül szeretném megköszönni azt a hatalmas szeretetet, amit az elmúlt hetekben megtapasztaltam,
s amin még az amerikaiak sem változtathatnak.
Rendkívül sokat jelent számomra ez a támogatás! Hálás vagyok Nektek!
Ha a szinkronban ezúttal nem is, más produkciók kapcsán még biztosan találkozunk.
Addig is ott vannak a régi részek 😉
Áldás,
Sinkovits-Vitay András

author: @Okazu84
comment:
And that was me disqualifying, cancelling, wiping away, de-indexing, closing, ignoring, yelling, yawning at every single suggestion of that trailer as yet another quality fan-made trailer, believing Jackman was (sadly) a man of his word when it came to Logan's ultimate fate in the film of the same name, that happened to be one of the most disturbing, obscure and mature iterations of the franchise's darkest timeline yet.

And then, I watched. And my mind exploded. Texting and sending frenetic audios to all my fan friends that laugh back at me since I'm SO late to the party.

I clicked on this trailer posted on a non-official channel believing I would at least enjoy a quality artist view of what "could have been in another Earth". I dreamed, hoped, waiting, thought, obsessed so many times, in so many forms, for so many years, randomly googling any piece of news that could have the slightest connection to such a revival that I had somehow completely made peace with leaving the most glorious past where it belonged, behind us, with our best memories to cherish about it.

And suddenly, the OFFICIAL Wolverine jumped, roared, swore, drank, was such a marvelous piece of tortured trash again and then shined on the savage battlefied, with non other than Reynold's Deadpool.

This cannot be real.

Yet, it is.

I , LOVE, MY, SILLY, DAY.

It looks like Cassandra Nova may be portrayed accurately to her comic source, which I'll be very happy with.

Alioth appearing makes me wonder if he's the greater threat of the story while Cassandra Nova is the main focused villain. Either way, I'm intrigued.

"You were THE X-Man." Well to a certain nostalgic crowd sure, but there's a lot of other X-Men fans would personally call other X-Men "THE X-Man. But that's a whole flame war nobody really wants to get into I'm sure.

author: @Lopez03Eduardo.
comment:
"This Wolverine let down his entire world"-Paradox
Paradox is sort of right in some timelines Logan succeeds saving X-Men and mutant kind while other timelines he doesn't succeed and fails.
"There’s a theory in quantum physics that time is immutable it’s like a river you can throw a pebble in and create a ripple but the current always corrects itself. No matter what you do the river just keeps flowing in the same direction"-Hank/Beast
What if the X-Men are always meant to die in every timeline and leaving Logan to be destined to outlive everyone he ever loved and become the last X Man left regardless how many times he and X-Men try to change the timeline.
Logan and X-Men prevented Sentinels and erased original trilogy and the Wolverine timeline creating new timeline (X-Men First Class, DOFP, Apocalypse, Dark Phoenix, New Mutants, and Dead Pool films) where mutants are alive and become pop culture heroes similar to what MCU Avengers have become in their universe.
Before you say Logan 2017 takes place in this new timeline and film is set five years after Days of Future Past I'm going by what was briefly discussed in the Making of Logan bonus feature with Hugh Jackman and James Mangold they intended for Logan to take place in a separate alternate timeline and when before film was released Mangold and Jackman did say it's set in an alternate timeline.
Logan 2017 alternate timeline instead of Sentinels who wipe out all mutants its someone from Logan's past Rice who distributed a formula that was supposedly designed to repress the mutant gene through soft drinks and breakfast cereals but it ended up killing mutants en masse his plan was to eliminate the existing mutants so that he could start over and create his own mutants to be born, bred, and sold as weapons which leaves Logan as last survivor and final X Man. So no matter how many times Logan and X-Men are the pebble thrown into timeline (river) create a ripple but the current corrects itself no matter what they do the timeline will keep flowing the same direction extinction of mutant kind.

author: @WolverineMRD
comment: OK so here are my speculations. Based on both trailers, we see Deadpool approaching a Wolverine dressed up as "patch" in the first trailer, and then in this one we see him approaching Wolverine in a bar (possibly for the first time) so I'm thinking that at least 2 different Wolverines (Variants) confirmed. The TVA recruits Deadpool because of his healing factor and his fighting skills because they are AFRAID of approaching any Wolverine variants to capture them (for whatever reason) so they need Deadpool's help with that because he's the only one who can do it (fight a Wolverine variant and survive), now I'm expecting that the TVA tricks Deadpool because we see him killing TVA agents in the trailer so they either lie to him about why they want these Wolverine variants captured/pruned, or he just discovers something he doesn't like right after he succeeds in capturing Wolverine because we see him lying on the ground so either way Deadpool ends up turning against them but he and this Wolverine get pruned as well and get sent to the Void at the end of time (where we see the 20th century fox logo) because we also see Alioth (the cloudy looking creature) in the trailer which we saw for the first time in the LOKI series. Now we also hear Deadpool saying ("I'm about to lose everything that I ever cared about" and "I don't know anything about saving worlds") and I did say earlier that he discovers something he doesn't like so that could be that he discovers that the TVA wants to prune/erase his reality (Deadpool's reality)!! So that means Vanessa, Dopinder, Al, and all the others that we see in the trailer will be gone forever and it's possibly because in his last movie Deadpool went back in time to save Vanessa (which is something that he's not supposed to do based on how the TVA works) so Deadpool starts to try and convince Wolverine to help him save his world (giving him a chance for redemption for failing to save his own) as well as finding a way to get out of the void and back to the TVA to stop them in time. I don't know if the Dr. Strange portal has anything to do with getting them out or not but they will be encountering lots of characters along the way possibly other variants. But the real villain here is the TVA. At least that's what I think, but I could be wrong though. Either way I think at least some of it is real based on what the trailer shows. At least some of it makes sense. Don't you agree?

Noticed:

- Wolverine in a bar again with a rude bartender, just like X-Men 1
- Claw trouble again, like in Logan
- "Go f*** yourself." (like X-Men: First Class)
- Alioth. {Where's Renslayer?)
- Pretty sure the Giant-Man head is a jab at Quantumania.

- The inclusion of "Like a Prayer" is possibly more important than it seems. The background behind it might be dazzling.

author: @nateborie6329
comment:
Two things:
1.) THANK YOU DISNEY! You have officially grown up and allowed something like this to rear its beautiful head. Absolutely perfect. It doesn't feel like a single beat of comedy is missed, and seeing Jackman and Reynolds together like this is absolutely perfect.
2.) I love the design for Logan's claws. I'm going to keep commenting on them. That partial dull blade tip, and the deeper shade of silver is just epic. And it looks like Jackman has barely stepped away from the role of Wolverine. You can take the Jackman away from the animal, but you can't take the animal away from the Jackman, and I can already see myself dying of laughter when this comes out.
